President Trump visited Michigan to speak to leaders, workers, engineers, and suppliers of major car companies such as Ford, Fiat-Chrysler, and General Motors. He promised to fight for Michigan workers and keep automobile production in the United States. He also announced plans to work on the CAFE (Corporate Average Fuel Economy) standards to support American car manufacturing. Trump emphasized the importance of buying American and hiring American, and vowed to crack down on foreign cheating and protect American jobs. He mentioned that jobs are already coming back to the US, and that his administration will work to eliminate industry-killing regulations and lower taxes. Trump also criticized previous administrations for allowing unfair trade practices and losing manufacturing jobs, and announced the withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP). He pledged to protect American industries, care for its people, and strengthen the country's manufacturing sector.